15 WHEREAS, in the United States, Black women are three to four times more likely to die of
16 pregnancy related causes than non-Hispanic white women, which is a disparity that cannot
17 be fully explained by differences in access to prenatal care, socioeconomic status, and
18 general physical health; and
19 WHEREAS, a key objective of the Georgia Department of Public Health is to reduce health
20 and mental health disparities among vulnerable and underserved communities and to achieve
21 health equity throughout Georgia, which should include health equity for Black pregnant
22 women and infants; and
23 WHEREAS, statistics have shown that Georgia has one of the highest maternal mortality
24 rates in the United States at almost twice the national rate; and
25 WHEREAS, in Georgia, Black women are almost three times more likely to die of pregnancy
26 related causes than non-Hispanic white women; and
27 WHEREAS, Georgia has experienced a string of hospital labor and delivery closures across
28 the state, especially in rural areas; and
29 WHEREAS, in Georgia, 34.6 percent of counties are defined as maternity care deserts,
30 compared to 32.6 percent in the United States; and
31 WHEREAS, chronic health conditions, such as cardiovascular disease, hypertension, obesity,
32 and diabetes, contribute to high rates of maternal morbidity and mortality, and, in Georgia,
33 Black women have egregious above-average rates of all of these conditions, resulting in
34 high-risk pregnancies and poor maternal health outcomes; and
