35 WHEREAS, Medicaid coverage for doula care during pregnancy, birth, and postpartum is
36 linked to improved maternal and infant health outcomes, as doula-assisted mothers were four
37 times less likely to have a baby with low birth weight, two times less likely to experience a
38 birth complication for the mother or infant, and significantly more likely to initiate
39 breastfeeding; and
40 WHEREAS, access to quality prenatal, perinatal, and postpartum care is essential to
41 improving Black maternal health outcomes and reducing preventable maternal deaths; and
42 WHEREAS, the establishment of a dedicated Georgia legislative Black Maternal Health
43 Caucus will provide the necessary framework to research, develop, and recommend
44 evidence-based policies and programs to improve maternal health in Georgia; and
45 WHEREAS, the establishment of a Georgia legislative Black Maternal Health Caucus will
46 serve as a coalition of members dedicated to increasing awareness and raising issues related
47 to poor maternal health outcomes and disparities among Black women, including
48 disproportionately high rates of maternal morbidity and mortality compared to their white
49 counterparts.
50 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES that
51 the members of this body urge the General Assembly to create a Georgia legislative Black
52 Maternal Health Caucus as a venue for members to organize around Georgia's maternal
53 health crisis and advance policy solutions to improve maternal health outcomes and end
54 disparities.
